[[Image:Richard Stuart Lake.jpg|thumb|The Hon. Richard Stuart Lake]]
'''Richard Stuart Lake''' ([[July 10]], [[1860]] &ndash; [[April 23]], [[1950]]) was a long serving territorial provincial and federal level politician from [[Saskatchewan]], [[Canada]].

==Territorial politics==
Born in [[Preston]], [[Lancashire]], [[England]], Lake was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of the Northwest Territories]] for the [[Grenfell (N.W.T. electoral district)|Grenfell]] district in the [[Northwest Territories general election, 1898|1898 Northwest Territories general election]]. In 1900 he vacated his seat to run in [[Assiniboia East]] in the [[Canadian federal election, 1900|1900 Canadian federal election]]. 

After being defeated in his first attempt at federal politics he ran for his old seat and was re-elected as the MLA in a by-election on [[March 22]], [[1901]].

Lake was acclaimed to his second term in office in the [[Northwest Territories general election, 1902|1902 Northwest Territories general election]]. He held that post until the [[Canadian federal election, 1904|1904 Canadian federal election]] when he vacated his seat to make a second run at Federal politics.

==Federal politics==
Lake was elected as a Member of the [[Canadian House of Commons]] in his second run at Federal politics in the [[Canadian federal election, 1904|1904 Canadian federal election]] in the new Qu'Appelle federal electoral district.

He was re-elected to a second term in the [[Canadian federal election, 1908|1908 Canadian federal election]] winning a hotly contested election by just a 100 votes.

In the [[Canadian federal election, 1911|1911 Canadian federal election]] he was defeated by [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] [[Levi Thompson]] and never returned to federal politics.

==Saskatchewan Lieutenant Governor==
After being defeated in the Federal election, Lake went to work for the Saskatchewan Public Service Commission, he held that job until he was appointed as [[Lieutenant Governor of Saskatchewan]] on [[October 18]], [[1915]]. He served for six years, until [[February 17]], [[1921]], when he was offered the possibility of extending his royal commission; however, he refused.

==Late life==
He moved to [[Victoria, British Columbia]] after his career in politics and lived the rest of his life there.

He was aboard the [[SS Athenia]] when it was torpedoed on [[September 3]], [[1939]] and survived.

He passed away on [[April 23]], [[1950]]

